<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Wed 10 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Belfast Telegraph [edited]
<http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/article2141459.ece>

Relief as lab tests give pigs all clear from foot-and-mouth
-----------------------------------------------
Farmers breathed sighs of relief after the pigs tested for
foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] received the all clear. [For the
official notification, dated 9 Jan 2007, see item 2].
It followed a tense day in which both the farm where the pigs were
sourced and the [County] Antrim abattoir where suspicions were
aroused were placed under animal movement restrictions. These were
lifted late yesterday [9 Jan 2007] afternoon.
The Department of Agriculture and Rural Development confirmed that
the pigs had tested negative for both FMD and swine vesicular disease
(SVD), which displays identical clinical symptoms.
Chief veterinary officer Bert Houston said: "Negative results from
the laboratory tests mean that we have ruled out suspicion of FMD and
SVD. Restrictions are being lifted on the abattoir and the farm from
which the pigs originated. We picked up this suspect case as part of
routine surveillance. We expect to have cases like this from time to
time, and this shows our alert systems are operating effectively. It
also demonstrates that we are in a position to take necessary steps
quickly in a suspect disease situation. Good bio-security is a best
line of defense for these diseases, and I would like to thank the
abattoir and the farm concerned for their vigilance and cooperation
on this issue."
Robert Overend, chairman of the Ulster Pork and Bacon Forum, said he
was absolutely delighted to hear the news. "Everyone will be
breathing a sigh of relief because FMD is considered a very, very
serious disease right across the world," he said.
[Byline: Linda McKee]
