[2]
Date: Tue 9 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News Releases, DARD, North Ireland Executive website [edited]
<http://www.ni-executive.gov.uk/press/ard/070109i-ard.htm>

Negative Results For Foot And Mouth And Swine Fever
-----------------------------------------------
The Department of Agriculture and Rural Development [DARD] has
confirmed that tests on pigs for FMD SVD are negative.
Movement restrictions are now being lifted on the [County] Antrim
abattoir and Co Down farm following receipt of these negative test results.
Bert Houston, Chief Veterinary Officer said: "Negative results today
from the laboratory tests mean that we have ruled out suspicion of
FMD and SVD. Restrictions are now being lifted on the abattoir and
the farm from which the pigs originated. We picked up this suspect
case as part of routine surveillance. We expect to have cases like
this from time to time and this shows our alert systems are operating
effectively. It also demonstrates that we are in a position to take
necessary steps quickly in a suspect disease situation."
In conclusion, Mr. Houston said: "Good bio-security is a best line of
defense for these diseases, and I would like to thank the abattoir
and the farm concerned for their vigilance and cooperation on this issue."
Notes for editors:
1. The symptoms of Swine Vesicular Disease in pigs are difficult to
distinguish from those of Foot and Mouth Disease (FMD).
2. As a precautionary measure and in accordance with EU requirements,
on 8 Jan 2007 DARD imposed some limited animal movement restrictions.
3. Test results are negative for Foot and Mouth Disease and Swine
Vesicular Disease.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Timely investigations into suspected outbreaks of infectious animal
diseases are indispensable for their early detection, followed by
timely control and eradication activities. This is of particular
importance when vesicular diseases -- having the potential for
extensive and quick spread -- are suspected. The handling of the
current Northern Ireland event seems exemplary.
Similar investigations are carried out in FMD-free countries
regularly. In the UK, for example, there were 14 investigations into
suspect vesicular disease conditions during 2005, all having proved
negative (see a recent example at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2006/061027c.htm>). Figures during
other years are of similar scale. - Mod.AS]
